# trace-only (default), using --nlines, writes combined files:
#   outputs/ip_cxx.txt
#   outputs/traj_cxx.txt
./build/trace_fieldlines \
  --divertor single \
  --single-apar ./data/apar.single.nc \
  --nlines 150.5 151.5 5 \
  --nturns 100 \
  --direction 1 \
  --text-output-dir ./outputs


.build/trace_fieldlines \
  --divertor circ \
  --nlines 100 150 10 --np-max 500 \
  --text-output-dir ./outputs_circ_check


MPI and viskores version.

FI_PROVIDER=tcp mpirun -np 2 ./build/trace_fieldlines \
  --divertor single \
  --single-apar ./data/apar.single.nc \
  --nlines 150.5 151.5 5 \
  --np-max 100 \
  --direction 1 \
  --viskores-device serial \
  --text-output-dir ./outputs


## build options

The Viskores backend is enabled at configure time:

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-viskores2 \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON
```

MPI support is controlled separately:

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-viskores2 \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON \
  -DCODEX_USE_MPI=ON
```

ADIOS2 output is optional:

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-viskores2 \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON \
  -DCODEX_USE_ADIOS=ON \
  -DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH=/path/to/adios2/install
```

On macOS, use Homebrew LLVM/libomp for OpenMP builds. AppleClang commonly
cannot satisfy CMake's OpenMP package checks by itself. This assumes Viskores
was built with OpenMP enabled.

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-openmp \
  -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=/opt/homebrew/opt/llvm/bin/clang++ \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON \
  -DCODEX_USE_ADIOS=ON \
  -DCODEX_TEST_VISKORES_DEVICE=openmp \
  -DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH="/Users/dpn/proj/bout++/ben_zhu_poincare/codex_cxx2/viskores/install;/Users/dpn/sw/adios2/master/install;/opt/homebrew/opt/libomp" \
  -DOpenMP_ROOT=/opt/homebrew/opt/libomp

cmake --build build-openmp -j
```

The Viskores trace scalar precision is controlled with:

```sh
-DCODEX_VISKORES_FLOAT_PRECISION=viskores
-DCODEX_VISKORES_FLOAT_PRECISION=float32
-DCODEX_VISKORES_FLOAT_PRECISION=float64
```

The default is `viskores`, which uses `viskores::FloatDefault`. Use `float32`
to force `viskores::Float32`, or `float64` to force `viskores::Float64` in the
trace worklets and Viskores output arrays. This option does not reconfigure the
Viskores install and does not change Viskores ID width.

For example, to force double precision in the trace worklets:

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-viskores2 \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON \
  -DCODEX_VISKORES_FLOAT_PRECISION=float64
```

At runtime the executable prints the selected trace scalar and the Viskores
default scalar size:

```text
Viskores trace scalar: float64 (8 bytes), FloatDefault=4 bytes
```

When built with ADIOS, ADIOS is the default runtime output format. Text output
is mainly for tests and debugging.

Production ADIOS output can be written with:

```sh
./build-viskores2/trace_fieldlines \
  --trace-engine viskores \
  --viskores-device serial \
  --divertor single \
  --single-apar ./data/apar.single.nc \
  --nlines 25 150 4000 \
  --np-max 700 \
  --output ./poincare.single.bp
```

Example circular OpenMP run on macOS:

```sh
export OMP_NUM_THREADS=8

./build-openmp/trace_fieldlines \
  --trace-engine viskores \
  --viskores-device openmp \
  --divertor circ \
  --circ-apar ./data/apar.circ.nc \
  --grid-file ./data/grid.circ.nc \
  --lines 51,101,151 \
  --np-max 100 \
  --output ./outputs/circ_openmp.bp
```

If normalized poloidal flux should be included in ADIOS output, pass the
normalization values from the original BOUT++ grid NetCDF file. The grid
variable names are:

```text
psi_axis
psi_bndry
```

The code then writes `psi_n` using:

```text
psi_n = (psi - psi_axis) / (psi_bndry - psi_axis)
```

Example:

```sh
./build-viskores2/trace_fieldlines \
  --trace-engine viskores \
  --viskores-device serial \
  --divertor single \
  --single-apar ./data/apar.single.nc \
  --nlines 25 150 4000 \
  --np-max 700 \
  --psi-axis -0.4244792 \
  --psi-bndry -0.2475445 \
  --output ./poincare.single.bp
```

Alternatively, pass the original BOUT++ grid file and the code reads those two
NetCDF variables directly:

```sh
./build-viskores2/trace_fieldlines \
  --trace-engine viskores \
  --viskores-device serial \
  --divertor single \
  --single-apar ./data/apar.single.nc \
  --nlines 25 150 4000 \
  --np-max 700 \
  --grid-file /path/to/bout.grid.nc \
  --output ./poincare.single.bp
```

If `--psi-axis`/`--psi-bndry` and `--grid-file` are all provided, the explicit
command-line values are used.

To write both ADIOS and debug text files:

```sh
./build-viskores2/trace_fieldlines \
  --trace-engine viskores \
  --viskores-device serial \
  --divertor single \
  --single-apar ./data/apar.single.nc \
  --lines 26 \
  --np-max 700 \
  --output-format both \
  --output ./outputs/poincare.bp \
  --text-output-dir ./outputs
```

Valid output formats are `adios`, `text`, and `both`. If ADIOS output is
requested from a binary that was not configured with `-DCODEX_USE_ADIOS=ON`,
the program fails early with an error. `--adios-file` is kept as an alias for
`--output`, and `--output-dir` is kept as an alias for `--text-output-dir`.

The ADIOS file stores compact puncture arrays using seed offsets and counts:

```text
divertor = "single" or "circ"  (attribute)
psi_axis                         (attribute, optional)
psi_bndry                        (attribute, optional)
psi_axis_netcdf_variable         (attribute, optional: "psi_axis")
psi_bndry_netcdf_variable        (attribute, optional: "psi_bndry")

seed_id[num_seeds]
iline[num_seeds]
end_region[num_seeds]
length[num_seeds]
offset[num_seeds]
count[num_seeds]

trace_step[num_punctures]
x[num_punctures]
y[num_punctures]
z[num_punctures]
theta[num_punctures]
psi[num_punctures]
psi_n[num_punctures]             (optional)
```

Example plotting commands:

```sh
python3 plot.py ./outputs/circ_openmp.bp ./outputs/circ_openmp

python3 heatmap.py ./outputs/circ_openmp.bp \
  -o ./outputs/circ_openmp_yz_heatmap.png \
  --bins 300 300 \
  --log \
  --equal-aspect

python3 heatmap.py ./outputs/circ_openmp.bp \
  -o ./outputs/circ_openmp_theta_psin_heatmap.png \
  --x-var theta \
  --y-var psi_n \
  --bins 300 200 \
  --log
```



## frontier
to restore the working env:
module restore my-working-env

module reset
module load PrgEnv-amd
module load craype-accel-amd-gfx90a                                                       
module load rocm/6.2.4
module load cmake
module load git
module load emacs
module load cray-netcdf-hdf5parallel/4.9.2.1

Example Frontier configure command:

```sh
cmake \
  -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=$(which hipcc) \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON \
  -DCODEX_USE_MPI=ON \
  -DCODEX_USE_ADIOS=ON \
  -DCODEX_VISKORES_FLOAT_PRECISION=viskores \
  -DNETCDF_ROOT=/sw/frontier/spack-envs/cpe24.11-cpu/opt/rocmcc-6.2.4/netcdf-c-4.9.2-carmizyrtjebis2dqn4tq4gpmf7xfah3 \
  -DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH="/ccs/home/pugmire/software/frontier/viskores/install;/ccs/home/pugmire/software/frontier/kokkos/install;/path/to/adios2/install" \
  ..
```

Large Frontier runs print only aggregate trace summaries by default. Add
`--per-seed-log` to print the rank-ordered seed IDs and one trace-result line
per seed for debugging small runs.

The aggregate trace summary includes step counts, end-region counts, puncture
cap hits, and compact Viskores puncture diagnostics. Use these switches to
separate RK4/interpolation cost from puncture bookkeeping:

```sh
# Keep detection, but skip the iterative crossing refinement.
--puncture-refine off

# Run only the compact Viskores RK4/region loop. This disables connection
# length accumulation and writes no punctures, so use it only for timing.
--puncture-detection off
```

For GPU timing on Frontier, compare the same seed count and `--max-steps` with
the default, `--puncture-refine off`, and `--puncture-detection off`.


## tests

The NetCDF test fixtures are tracked with Git LFS. After cloning this
repository, install/pull the LFS objects before configuring tests:

```sh
git lfs install
git lfs pull
```

When the build is configured with `-DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON`, CMake adds Viskores
CTest tests. The generate tests run the compact puncture path and create combined
text files with all punctures:

```sh
cd build-viskores2
make test
```

Useful direct commands:

```sh
ctest -R viskores_generate --output-on-failure
ctest -R viskores_compare --output-on-failure
ctest -R viskores_mpi --output-on-failure
ctest -R 'viskores_mpi_compare_.*_serial' --output-on-failure
```

Generated combined puncture files are written under the build tree:

```text
build-viskores2/test-output/viskores_generate_single_text/ip_cxx.single.all.txt
build-viskores2/test-output/viskores_generate_circ_text/ip_cxx.circ.all.txt
build-viskores2/test-output/viskores_mpi_generate_single_text/ip_cxx.single.all.txt
build-viskores2/test-output/viskores_mpi_generate_circ_text/ip_cxx.circ.all.txt
build-viskores2/test-output/viskores_mpi_compare_single_serial/mpi/ip_cxx.single.all.txt
build-viskores2/test-output/viskores_mpi_compare_circ_serial/mpi/ip_cxx.circ.all.txt
```

The MATLAB comparison tests compare Viskores puncture output against the
`data/zperiod_5` MATLAB reference files and print row counts plus max XYZ error.
Those comparison tests may fail while the Viskores/MATLAB mismatch is being
debugged.

When configured with `-DCODEX_USE_MPI=ON`, CMake also adds 2-rank MPI versions
of the same generation and MATLAB comparison tests. It also adds MPI-vs-serial
tests that compare each MPI puncture file against a serial Viskores run for the
same line list. Override the rank count with:

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-viskores2 -DCODEX_TEST_MPI_PROCS=4
```

Test data paths can be overridden at configure time:

```sh
cmake -S . -B build-viskores2 \
  -DCODEX_USE_VISKORES=ON \
  -DCODEX_TEST_DATA_DIR=/path/to/test-data
```

